/* CISM :: content/quiz1.js — CISM Domain 1 question bank (100 items). */
window.CISM = window.CISM || {}; CISM.questions = CISM.questions || [];
CISM.questions.push.apply(CISM.questions, [
{"id":"D1-001","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"An information security manager is developing an information security strategy. Which of the following should be the PRIMARY basis for that strategy?","options":["The organization's business objectives and risk appetite","Industry best practice frameworks","The prior year's security budget","Findings from the most recent penetration test"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The organization's business objectives and risk appetite</strong> — an effective security strategy exists to enable and protect business goals within the level of risk the organization is willing to accept; everything else is derived from that alignment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Industry best practice frameworks</b>: useful reference material, but adopting them without regard to business context can misalign security investment with actual needs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The prior year's security budget</b>: a budget is a resourcing constraint, not a strategic driver, and should follow strategy rather than define it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Findings from the most recent penetration test</b>: these are tactical, point-in-time technical inputs and too narrow to anchor an enterprise strategy.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-002","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the relationship between information security governance and corporate governance?","options":["Information security governance is a subset of corporate governance","Information security governance is unrelated to corporate governance","Corporate governance is a subset of information security governance","The two are identical in scope and function"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Information security governance is a subset of corporate governance</strong> — it extends overall enterprise governance principles into the domain of protecting information assets, ensuring security decisions support broader fiduciary and oversight responsibilities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Information security governance is unrelated to corporate governance</b>: this ignores that security governance derives its authority and accountability structures from corporate governance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Corporate governance is a subset of information security governance</b>: this reverses the actual hierarchy; security governance is the narrower, dependent discipline.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The two are identical in scope and function</b>: corporate governance covers all enterprise domains (financial, operational, legal), while security governance is domain-specific.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-003","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"An information security manager wants to obtain sustained senior management commitment to the security program. Which of the following is the MOST effective way to achieve this?","options":["Presenting risk in business terms and linking it to organizational objectives","Distributing security awareness posters throughout the office","Requiring all staff to sign an acceptable use policy","Publishing technical vulnerability scan results monthly"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Presenting risk in business terms and linking it to organizational objectives</strong> — senior management engages and commits resources when they understand how security risk affects revenue, reputation, and strategic goals, not when shown raw technical data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Distributing security awareness posters throughout the office</b>: this raises general staff awareness but does not influence executive-level commitment or funding decisions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requiring all staff to sign an acceptable use policy</b>: this is a compliance control for end users, not a mechanism for securing executive sponsorship.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publishing technical vulnerability scan results monthly</b>: technical detail without business context is unlikely to resonate with or motivate senior management.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-004","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following roles is PRIMARILY accountable for ensuring that an organization's information assets are adequately protected?","options":["Information security manager","Data custodian","Data owner","Chief information officer"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data owner</strong> — the data owner holds ultimate accountability for classifying data and ensuring it is protected at a level commensurate with its value and risk, even though day-to-day protection may be delegated.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Information security manager</b>: this role designs, implements, and coordinates the security program but is not the accountable business owner of the asset.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data custodian</b>: custodians implement controls and safeguard data on behalf of the owner but do not hold accountability for protection decisions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Chief information officer</b>: the CIO typically owns technology delivery and infrastructure, not accountability for the protection of specific information assets.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-005","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"The MOST important reason for an information security manager to align the security strategy with enterprise architecture is to:","options":["Ensure security controls are integrated consistently across technology investments","Reduce the cost of security awareness training","Simplify the vendor selection process","Eliminate the need for a risk assessment"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Ensure security controls are integrated consistently across technology investments</strong> — enterprise architecture alignment ensures security is embedded by design into future technology decisions rather than bolted on inconsistently after the fact.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the cost of security awareness training</b>: enterprise architecture alignment has no direct bearing on awareness training costs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Simplify the vendor selection process</b>: this may be a minor side benefit but is not the primary purpose of architectural alignment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for a risk assessment</b>: architecture alignment does not remove the ongoing need to assess risk; it complements it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-006","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST indicates the maturity of an organization's information security governance?","options":["The number of security tools deployed","The existence of a documented incident response plan","The degree to which security roles, metrics, and reporting are embedded in business processes","The frequency of firewall rule changes"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The degree to which security roles, metrics, and reporting are embedded in business processes</strong> — mature governance is evidenced by security being institutionalized into how the organization operates and makes decisions, not by isolated artifacts or tool counts.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of security tools deployed</b>: tool quantity reflects spending, not governance maturity, and may even indicate poor integration.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The existence of a documented incident response plan</b>: having a single document is a baseline control, not a comprehensive measure of governance maturity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The frequency of firewall rule changes</b>: this is an operational metric unrelated to governance structure or maturity.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-007","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"hard","q":"An information security steering committee is being formed. Which of the following membership characteristics would BEST support effective governance decisions?","options":["Representation from key business units, legal, and executive management","Membership limited to IT and security personnel","Rotating membership selected at random each quarter","Membership restricted to external consultants for objectivity"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Representation from key business units, legal, and executive management</strong> — a steering committee needs cross-functional representation so that security decisions reflect business priorities, legal obligations, and have the authority to be enforced.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Membership limited to IT and security personnel</b>: this creates a technology-only view and risks decisions that are disconnected from business risk appetite.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rotating membership selected at random each quarter</b>: random rotation undermines continuity, institutional knowledge, and consistent decision-making.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Membership restricted to external consultants for objectivity</b>: outsiders lack the organizational authority and context needed to drive internal accountability.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-008","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the MOST important factor when selecting an information security governance framework?","options":["The framework's fit with the organization's size, culture, and regulatory environment","The framework's popularity among competitors","The framework requiring the least documentation","The vendor offering the lowest certification cost"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The framework's fit with the organization's size, culture, and regulatory environment</strong> — a governance framework must be tailored and applicable to the specific organizational context to be effective and sustainable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The framework's popularity among competitors</b>: popularity elsewhere does not guarantee suitability for a different organization's risk profile or culture.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The framework requiring the least documentation</b>: minimizing documentation should never outweigh selecting a framework that actually addresses the organization's risks.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The vendor offering the lowest certification cost</b>: cost of certification is a minor procurement consideration, not a governance fit criterion.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-009","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"hard","q":"A new information security manager finds that security policies exist but are inconsistently enforced across business units. What should be done FIRST?","options":["Determine the root cause of inconsistent enforcement","Immediately terminate employees found violating policy","Rewrite all policies from scratch","Outsource policy enforcement to a third party"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Determine the root cause of inconsistent enforcement</strong> — understanding why enforcement varies (e.g., unclear accountability, lack of resources, cultural resistance) is necessary before selecting a corrective action that will actually solve the problem.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately terminate employees found violating policy</b>: this is a punitive reaction that does not address systemic causes and may be disproportionate or unjust.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rewrite all policies from scratch</b>: rewriting policies is premature if the existing policies are adequate and the issue is enforcement, not content.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Outsource policy enforcement to a third party</b>: outsourcing does not resolve the underlying governance gap and abdicates management accountability.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-010","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"Who is ULTIMATELY accountable for information security within an organization?","options":["Senior management/the board of directors","The information security manager","The IT help desk","The internal audit function"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Senior management/the board of directors</strong> — ultimate accountability for the organization's risk posture, including information security, rests with governing bodies, even though operational responsibility is delegated.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The information security manager</b>: this role is responsible for executing and managing the program but is not the ultimate accountable party.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The IT help desk</b>: the help desk performs operational support tasks and has no governance accountability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The internal audit function</b>: audit provides independent assurance and oversight but does not hold accountability for security outcomes.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-011","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"An information security strategy is considered effective when it:","options":["Enables business objectives while managing risk to an acceptable level","Eliminates all identified risks","Requires no periodic review","Focuses exclusively on regulatory compliance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Enables business objectives while managing risk to an acceptable level</strong> — the purpose of a security strategy is to support the organization in achieving its goals while keeping risk within the defined risk appetite, not to achieve zero risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminates all identified risks</b>: eliminating all risk is neither feasible nor cost-effective; some residual risk is always accepted.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requires no periodic review</b>: strategies must be reviewed and adjusted as the business and threat landscape evolve.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Focuses exclusively on regulatory compliance</b>: compliance is one input, but a strategy limited to compliance may leave significant business risks unaddressed.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-012","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which metric would BEST demonstrate to the board that the information security program is delivering value?","options":["Reduction in business impact from security incidents over time","Number of security policies published","Number of firewalls installed","Total headcount of the security team"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reduction in business impact from security incidents over time</strong> — boards care about outcomes that affect the business; a measurable decline in incident impact ties the program directly to risk reduction and value delivered.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of security policies published</b>: policy volume is an output measure with no direct correlation to actual risk reduction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of firewalls installed</b>: this is an input/asset count that says nothing about effectiveness or business value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Total headcount of the security team</b>: staffing levels reflect investment, not the value or effectiveness of the program.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-013","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is restructuring and consolidating multiple business unit security functions under a single CISO. Which governance benefit is MOST significant from this change?","options":["Consistent application of risk appetite and policy across the enterprise","Reduced need for security awareness training","Elimination of all business unit security budgets","Guaranteed regulatory compliance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Consistent application of risk appetite and policy across the enterprise</strong> — centralizing governance under one accountable executive ensures uniform standards, reduces conflicting practices, and improves enterprise-wide risk visibility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduced need for security awareness training</b>: consolidation does not reduce the ongoing need to train staff across the enterprise.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Elimination of all business unit security budgets</b>: budgets may be reallocated or centralized but are not eliminated; funding for security still exists.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guaranteed regulatory compliance</b>: centralization improves consistency but does not by itself guarantee compliance with all applicable regulations.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-014","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"COBIT distinguishes between governance and management primarily by stating that governance:","options":["Evaluates, directs, and monitors, while management plans, builds, runs, and monitors","Executes day-to-day security operations","Is performed solely by the IT department","Is only relevant to publicly traded companies"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Evaluates, directs, and monitors, while management plans, builds, runs, and monitors</strong> — COBIT defines governance as setting direction and monitoring outcomes at the oversight level, while management executes activities to achieve those objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Executes day-to-day security operations</b>: day-to-day execution is a management function, not a governance one.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Is performed solely by the IT department</b>: governance is an enterprise-level responsibility involving the board and executive leadership, not just IT.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Is only relevant to publicly traded companies</b>: governance principles apply to organizations of all types and ownership structures.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-015","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"An information security manager is asked to justify continued investment in the security program to the audit committee. The BEST approach is to present:","options":["Risk-based metrics showing trends in exposure reduction and control effectiveness","A list of every security incident from the past decade","The résumés of the security team members","A comparison of security tool brand names used by competitors"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Risk-based metrics showing trends in exposure reduction and control effectiveness</strong> — decision-makers need quantifiable, trend-based evidence that investment is reducing risk and improving control performance to justify continued funding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A list of every security incident from the past decade</b>: an exhaustive incident list is not analyzed or actionable and does not demonstrate value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The résumés of the security team members</b>: staff qualifications do not answer the question of program effectiveness or risk reduction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A comparison of security tool brand names used by competitors</b>: this is irrelevant competitive information, not evidence of the program's own value.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-016","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST demonstrates that information security governance is integrated with corporate governance?","options":["Security risk is a standing agenda item at board and executive meetings","The security team has its own separate mission statement","Security policies are stored on the corporate intranet","The security manager reports informally to the IT director"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Security risk is a standing agenda item at board and executive meetings</strong> — integration is demonstrated when security risk is routinely considered alongside other enterprise risks in top-level decision-making forums.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The security team has its own separate mission statement</b>: a standalone mission statement can actually signal disconnection from overall corporate strategy rather than integration.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Security policies are stored on the corporate intranet</b>: document accessibility is an administrative detail, not evidence of governance integration.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The security manager reports informally to the IT director</b>: informal reporting lines without governance visibility suggest weak, not strong, integration.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-017","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"hard","q":"During strategy development, an information security manager discovers that the desired future state conflicts with the current organizational culture. What is the BEST course of action?","options":["Develop a roadmap that includes cultural change management alongside technical initiatives","Abandon the strategy and maintain the status quo","Implement the strategy immediately without regard to culture","Delay the strategy indefinitely until culture changes on its own"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Develop a roadmap that includes cultural change management alongside technical initiatives</strong> — successful strategy execution requires addressing the human and cultural gap through structured change management, not ignoring or waiting on it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Abandon the strategy and maintain the status quo</b>: abandoning the strategy leaves the organization exposed and fails to address the identified gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Implement the strategy immediately without regard to culture</b>: ignoring cultural resistance significantly increases the risk of failed adoption and pushback.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delay the strategy indefinitely until culture changes on its own</b>: culture rarely shifts without deliberate intervention, so indefinite delay is not a viable plan.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-018","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"The PRIMARY purpose of an information security strategy is to:","options":["Provide a long-term roadmap that aligns security initiatives with business goals","Document every technical control in detail","Replace the need for an information security policy","Satisfy a single regulatory audit requirement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Provide a long-term roadmap that aligns security initiatives with business goals</strong> — the strategy sets direction and priorities over time so that security initiatives support and enable organizational objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Document every technical control in detail</b>: detailed control documentation belongs in standards and procedures, not the strategic plan.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for an information security policy</b>: strategy and policy serve different, complementary purposes; one does not replace the other.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Satisfy a single regulatory audit requirement</b>: a strategy addresses ongoing enterprise needs, not a one-time compliance checkbox.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-019","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the MOST appropriate action when a new law introduces data protection requirements that affect the organization's operations?","options":["Assess the impact on current policies and controls, then update the security strategy accordingly","Wait for a customer complaint before taking action","Immediately shut down the affected business process","Delegate the entire matter to the legal department with no security involvement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Assess the impact on current policies and controls, then update the security strategy accordingly</strong> — proactively evaluating regulatory change ensures the security program remains compliant and that gaps are addressed before they result in violations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Wait for a customer complaint before taking action</b>: reactive compliance exposes the organization to legal and reputational risk that proactive action would prevent.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately shut down the affected business process</b>: this is an extreme, disproportionate response before the actual impact and required changes are even understood.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delegate the entire matter to the legal department with no security involvement</b>: security must be involved since implementation of technical and procedural controls falls within its scope.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-020","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"med","q":"An organization's information security policy has not been updated in five years. The GREATEST concern for the information security manager should be that the policy:","options":["May no longer reflect current risks, technology, and regulatory requirements","Uses outdated formatting and templates","Was not translated into multiple languages","Does not include a revision history table"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>May no longer reflect current risks, technology, and regulatory requirements</strong> — an outdated policy risks leaving new threats, technologies, and legal obligations unaddressed, undermining the effectiveness of governance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Uses outdated formatting and templates</b>: formatting is a cosmetic issue with no bearing on the policy's substantive adequacy.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Was not translated into multiple languages</b>: translation is a communication consideration, secondary to whether the content itself is current and relevant.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Does not include a revision history table</b>: a missing revision log is an administrative gap, not a substantive governance risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-021","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"hard","q":"An enterprise uses COBIT as its governance framework. During an assessment, the information security manager notes that management processes are well defined but there is no formal mechanism for the board to direct or monitor security investment decisions. This represents a gap in:","options":["Governance practices","Management practices only","Technical control design","Incident response procedures"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Governance practices</strong> — the absence of a board-level mechanism to evaluate, direct, and monitor security investment is specifically a governance gap, since governance is the layer responsible for oversight and direction-setting.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Management practices only</b>: the scenario states management processes are well defined, so the deficiency lies above management, at the governance layer.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Technical control design</b>: the issue described is about oversight and direction, not the design of specific technical controls.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Incident response procedures</b>: nothing in the scenario relates to how incidents are handled.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-022","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the MOST important prerequisite for obtaining senior management support for information security initiatives?","options":["Clear communication of business risk in terms executives understand","A large security budget already approved","A fully staffed security operations center","Certification of all security staff"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Clear communication of business risk in terms executives understand</strong> — executives commit support and resources when they grasp how security risk translates into business impact, expressed in language relevant to their decision-making.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A large security budget already approved</b>: budget approval is typically the outcome of gaining support, not a prerequisite for it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A fully staffed security operations center</b>: staffing level is an operational resource, not what drives executive buy-in.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Certification of all security staff</b>: individual certifications demonstrate technical competence but do not by themselves secure executive commitment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-023","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would provide the BEST evidence of alignment between the information security program and business strategy?","options":["Security initiatives mapped directly to specific business objectives and priorities","A high number of completed security projects in the past year","Positive feedback from a recent security awareness survey","Adoption of the latest security technology"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Security initiatives mapped directly to specific business objectives and priorities</strong> — direct traceability between security initiatives and business goals is the clearest evidence that the program supports what the organization is trying to achieve.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A high number of completed security projects in the past year</b>: project volume alone says nothing about whether those projects supported actual business priorities.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Positive feedback from a recent security awareness survey</b>: employee sentiment on awareness training does not demonstrate strategic alignment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Adoption of the latest security technology</b>: using new technology does not inherently mean it supports specific business objectives.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-024","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"med","q":"In a RACI model for information security governance, who should typically be identified as \"accountable\" for approving the enterprise risk appetite?","options":["Board of directors or senior executive management","Information security manager","Systems administrator","Help desk supervisor"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Board of directors or senior executive management</strong> — setting and approving the organization's risk appetite is a top-level governance decision that belongs to the board or senior executives who bear ultimate accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Information security manager</b>: this role recommends and operationalizes risk appetite but is not the accountable approver.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Systems administrator</b>: this is a technical operational role with no governance decision-making authority.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Help desk supervisor</b>: this role has no involvement in enterprise-level risk appetite decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-025","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager is developing a multi-year strategy. Which approach BEST balances current operational needs with long-term goals?","options":["Use a gap analysis between current and desired states to build a phased roadmap","Focus exclusively on emerging threats three to five years out","Implement all desired end-state controls immediately regardless of cost","Postpone all planning until the current fiscal year budget is finalized"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Use a gap analysis between current and desired states to build a phased roadmap</strong> — a gap analysis identifies what exists today versus the target state, enabling a realistic, prioritized, and phased plan that balances near-term needs with long-term vision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Focus exclusively on emerging threats three to five years out</b>: ignoring current operational gaps leaves near-term risks unaddressed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Implement all desired end-state controls immediately regardless of cost</b>: this is financially and operationally unrealistic and ignores prioritization based on risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Postpone all planning until the current fiscal year budget is finalized</b>: strategic planning should inform budgeting, not be held hostage to it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-026","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager wants to select key performance indicators (KPIs) for board reporting. The BEST KPIs are those that are:","options":["Highly technical and detailed for full transparency","Selected by the IT department without business input","Tied to business outcomes, actionable, and trend-based","Changed every quarter to keep reporting current"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tied to business outcomes, actionable, and trend-based</strong> — effective board-level KPIs translate security performance into business-relevant, trackable indicators that support informed decision-making over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Highly technical and detailed for full transparency</b>: excessive technical detail obscures rather than clarifies business risk for a board audience.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Selected by the IT department without business input</b>: KPIs chosen in isolation from the business are unlikely to reflect what matters most to decision-makers.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Changed every quarter to keep reporting current</b>: constantly changing metrics prevents meaningful trend analysis over time.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-027","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY reason information security objectives must be reviewed periodically?","options":["To satisfy an annual paperwork requirement","To increase the size of the security budget","Because business objectives, threats, and regulations change over time","To provide work for compliance staff"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Because business objectives, threats, and regulations change over time</strong> — periodic review ensures that security objectives remain relevant and effective as the internal business context and external threat/regulatory landscape evolve.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To satisfy an annual paperwork requirement</b>: treating review as a mere formality misses its actual risk management purpose.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To increase the size of the security budget</b>: budget growth is not the goal of a periodic objectives review.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To provide work for compliance staff</b>: review exists to maintain relevance and effectiveness, not to generate busywork.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-028","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"hard","q":"A steering committee consistently defers security-related decisions due to disagreements between business unit leaders. What should the information security manager do FIRST?","options":["Escalate every disagreement directly to the external auditor","Make unilateral decisions on behalf of the committee","Work with the committee chair to establish clear decision-making authority and escalation paths","Dissolve the steering committee"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Work with the committee chair to establish clear decision-making authority and escalation paths</strong> — resolving governance gridlock requires clarifying who has authority to decide and how unresolved issues are escalated, restoring effective governance function.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Escalate every disagreement directly to the external auditor</b>: auditors provide independent assurance, not operational governance decision-making.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Make unilateral decisions on behalf of the committee</b>: bypassing the committee undermines its authority and the cross-functional buy-in it is meant to provide.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Dissolve the steering committee</b>: eliminating the committee removes a needed governance structure rather than fixing its dysfunction.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-029","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST helps an information security manager gain and maintain the support of business unit leaders?","options":["Issuing mandates without consultation","Limiting all communication to email bulletins","Involving business unit leaders in risk decisions that affect their areas","Avoiding discussion of security costs"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Involving business unit leaders in risk decisions that affect their areas</strong> — engaging leaders as participants in decisions affecting their operations builds ownership, buy-in, and more informed, sustainable risk decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Issuing mandates without consultation</b>: top-down mandates without input often generate resistance and poor compliance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Limiting all communication to email bulletins</b>: one-way, impersonal communication does not build the relationship needed for ongoing support.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoiding discussion of security costs</b>: transparency about costs and trade-offs is necessary for leaders to make informed risk decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-030","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"When developing an information security strategy, which of the following should be identified FIRST?","options":["The specific security technologies to be purchased","The names of vendors to be engaged","The current state of security capabilities and the desired future state","The exact wording of the security policy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The current state of security capabilities and the desired future state</strong> — strategy development begins with understanding where the organization stands today versus where it needs to be, which then informs the roadmap and subsequent decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The specific security technologies to be purchased</b>: technology selection is a downstream implementation decision, not a starting point.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The names of vendors to be engaged</b>: vendor selection follows from defined requirements, which have not yet been established.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The exact wording of the security policy</b>: policy drafting occurs after strategic direction and objectives are set.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-031","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes an information security governance framework?","options":["A single technical control standard","A list of approved software vendors","A structure of policies, roles, processes, and metrics that directs and monitors security activity","A checklist used only during external audits"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A structure of policies, roles, processes, and metrics that directs and monitors security activity</strong> — a governance framework provides the overarching structure that ensures security activities are directed, resourced, and monitored consistently with enterprise objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single technical control standard</b>: a technical standard addresses one narrow control area, not the full governance structure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A list of approved software vendors</b>: a vendor list is a procurement artifact unrelated to governance structure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A checklist used only during external audits</b>: reducing governance to an audit checklist misrepresents its ongoing, operational nature.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-032","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"med","q":"The BEST way to ensure information security roles and responsibilities are understood across the organization is to:","options":["Rely on informal word-of-mouth communication","Assume all employees already understand their responsibilities","Formally document and communicate roles through policy, job descriptions, and training","Publish roles only in the security team's internal wiki"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Formally document and communicate roles through policy, job descriptions, and training</strong> — clarity and consistency in accountability require formal documentation and structured communication reaching all relevant stakeholders, not informal or assumed understanding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rely on informal word-of-mouth communication</b>: informal channels are inconsistent and unreliable for establishing accountability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assume all employees already understand their responsibilities</b>: assuming understanding without formal communication is a governance failure waiting to happen.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publish roles only in the security team's internal wiki</b>: limiting visibility to the security team excludes the broader organization that also holds security responsibilities.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-033","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"med","q":"An organization adopts ISO/IEC 27001 as part of its governance approach. The PRIMARY benefit of this standard is that it:","options":["Guarantees the organization will never suffer a breach","Replaces the need for a risk assessment","Provides a structured framework for establishing, operating, and improving an information security management system","Is legally mandated in every jurisdiction"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Provides a structured framework for establishing, operating, and improving an information security management system</strong> — ISO/IEC 27001 offers a systematic, internationally recognized approach to building and continually improving an ISMS aligned to organizational risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guarantees the organization will never suffer a breach</b>: no framework can guarantee immunity from breaches; it only helps manage risk more effectively.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replaces the need for a risk assessment</b>: risk assessment is actually a core, required component within the ISO/IEC 27001 framework, not something it replaces.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Is legally mandated in every jurisdiction</b>: ISO/IEC 27001 is a voluntary standard, not a universal legal mandate.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-034","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"hard","q":"An audit finds that the information security policy grants exceptions liberally without a formal approval or tracking process. What is the GREATEST risk this presents?","options":["Increased printing costs for policy documents","Delayed employee onboarding","Erosion of the policy's effectiveness and accumulation of unmanaged risk","Reduced need for security awareness training"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Erosion of the policy's effectiveness and accumulation of unmanaged risk</strong> — uncontrolled exceptions undermine the intent of the policy and allow risk to accumulate outside of visibility and management oversight.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increased printing costs for policy documents</b>: this is a trivial administrative concern unrelated to the real governance risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delayed employee onboarding</b>: exception handling for policy is unrelated to onboarding timelines.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduced need for security awareness training</b>: liberal exceptions do not reduce training needs; if anything, they increase the need for awareness of proper controls.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-035","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"An information security manager's business case for a new control should PRIMARILY emphasize:","options":["The technical specifications of the proposed solution","The vendor's marketing materials","How the control reduces risk relative to its cost and supports business objectives","The number of similar controls used by competitors"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>How the control reduces risk relative to its cost and supports business objectives</strong> — a compelling business case ties investment directly to risk reduction and business value, which is what resonates with decision-makers approving funding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The technical specifications of the proposed solution</b>: technical detail alone does not justify investment without linking it to risk and business value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The vendor's marketing materials</b>: marketing content is promotional and not a substitute for an objective risk-based justification.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of similar controls used by competitors</b>: competitor practices are a secondary reference point, not the primary justification.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-036","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager notices that a KPI showing \"100% of critical patches applied within SLA\" has remained flat for two years despite an increasing volume of vulnerabilities. What should the manager do FIRST?","options":["Accept the metric as evidence of a mature program","Remove the KPI from board reporting","Investigate whether the SLA and scope of the metric still reflect actual risk exposure","Increase the SLA timeframe to make the metric easier to achieve"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Investigate whether the SLA and scope of the metric still reflect actual risk exposure</strong> — a metric that stays perfect despite a changing risk environment may be poorly scoped or gamed, so its validity and relevance should be examined before it is trusted or reported further.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the metric as evidence of a mature program</b>: taking a suspiciously static metric at face value risks masking an underlying reporting or scope problem.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove the KPI from board reporting</b>: removing visibility does not address whether the underlying metric or process needs correction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the SLA timeframe to make the metric easier to achieve</b>: loosening the SLA to preserve a good-looking number would mask risk rather than manage it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-037","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would MOST likely cause an information security strategy to fail during implementation?","options":["Too much involvement from business unit leaders","Overly frequent strategy reviews","Lack of ongoing executive sponsorship and resource commitment","Excessive documentation of security metrics"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Lack of ongoing executive sponsorship and resource commitment</strong> — without sustained executive backing and resources, even a well-designed strategy will stall as competing priorities consume attention and funding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Too much involvement from business unit leaders</b>: business engagement generally strengthens, rather than undermines, strategy execution.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Overly frequent strategy reviews</b>: regular reviews help keep a strategy relevant and are not a typical cause of failure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Excessive documentation of security metrics</b>: thorough metrics documentation supports informed decisions rather than causing strategic failure.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-038","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"med","q":"An organization operates in multiple countries with conflicting data protection laws. The information security manager's BEST approach is to:","options":["Apply only the home country's laws everywhere","Ignore conflicting requirements to simplify operations","Develop a policy baseline that meets the most stringent applicable requirement in each jurisdiction","Let each local office decide its own compliance approach independently"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Develop a policy baseline that meets the most stringent applicable requirement in each jurisdiction</strong> — building a compliant baseline that satisfies the strictest relevant requirements ensures lawful operation everywhere while maintaining consistency across the enterprise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Apply only the home country's laws everywhere</b>: this risks violating local laws in jurisdictions with stricter or different requirements.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore conflicting requirements to simplify operations</b>: ignoring legal obligations exposes the organization to regulatory penalties and legal risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Let each local office decide its own compliance approach independently</b>: decentralized, uncoordinated compliance decisions create inconsistency and gaps in enterprise oversight.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-039","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which document typically defines the high-level intent and direction of an organization's approach to protecting information assets?","options":["Standard operating procedure","Technical configuration guide","Information security policy","Vendor service level agreement"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Information security policy</strong> — the policy sets the overarching intent, direction, and expectations for protecting information assets, from which standards and procedures are subsequently derived.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Standard operating procedure</b>: procedures provide step-by-step instructions for specific tasks, at a lower level than policy.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Technical configuration guide</b>: this is a detailed implementation document, not a statement of high-level intent.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Vendor service level agreement</b>: an SLA defines contractual service terms with a vendor, not internal governance direction.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-040","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"med","q":"The information security manager reports to the chief information officer (CIO), who also controls the IT operations budget. Which of the following is the GREATEST concern with this reporting structure?","options":["The CIO may lack technical knowledge of security","The security manager will have too much authority","Potential conflict of interest between operational efficiency and security risk decisions","IT operations costs will decrease"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Potential conflict of interest between operational efficiency and security risk decisions</strong> — when the same executive controls both IT operations and security oversight, security priorities may be subordinated to cost, performance, or delivery pressures.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The CIO may lack technical knowledge of security</b>: this is a possible individual competency issue, not the structural governance concern posed by combined authority.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The security manager will have too much authority</b>: the scenario describes the opposite risk—security being subordinated to operations, not gaining excess authority.</span> <span class='qd'><b>IT operations costs will decrease</b>: cost reduction is not inherently a governance risk and is not the central concern here.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-041","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager presents a proposal to the board that would significantly reduce risk but requires a budget increase far beyond prior years. The board is hesitant. What is the BEST next step?","options":["Withdraw the proposal and abandon the initiative","Proceed with implementation without board approval","Present a phased approach with quantified risk reduction and cost-benefit analysis for each phase","Reduce the scope silently without informing the board of the risk trade-off"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Present a phased approach with quantified risk reduction and cost-benefit analysis for each phase</strong> — breaking the initiative into phases with clear, quantified value at each stage helps the board make an informed, incremental funding decision rather than an all-or-nothing choice.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Withdraw the proposal and abandon the initiative</b>: abandoning a risk-reducing initiative without exploring alternatives is premature and leaves risk unaddressed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Proceed with implementation without board approval</b>: bypassing governance approval undermines the oversight process and is inappropriate for major budget decisions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the scope silently without informing the board of the risk trade-off</b>: hiding the risk implications of a scope reduction from the board is a transparency failure.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-042","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the role of the NIST Cybersecurity Framework in an organization's governance program?","options":["It mandates specific technical products to be purchased","It replaces the need for a board-approved security strategy","It provides a common taxonomy and structure to describe and assess cybersecurity risk and maturity","It applies only to United States federal agencies"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>It provides a common taxonomy and structure to describe and assess cybersecurity risk and maturity</strong> — the framework offers a flexible, widely adopted structure (Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover) for organizations to communicate about and improve their risk posture.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It mandates specific technical products to be purchased</b>: the framework is technology-agnostic and does not prescribe specific vendor products.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It replaces the need for a board-approved security strategy</b>: the framework is a reference tool that supports, but does not substitute for, a governance-approved strategy.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It applies only to United States federal agencies</b>: while originating from a U.S. government initiative, it is voluntarily used by organizations worldwide across sectors.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-043","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's information security governance is assessed as ad hoc, with no formal processes and results that depend heavily on individual effort. According to common maturity models, this level BEST corresponds to:","options":["Optimized","Managed and measurable","Initial/ad hoc","Defined and documented"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Initial/ad hoc</strong> — this is the lowest maturity level in common models, characterized by inconsistent, undocumented processes that succeed or fail based on individual heroics rather than institutional capability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Optimized</b>: this is the highest maturity level, featuring continuous improvement, which contradicts the ad hoc description given.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Managed and measurable</b>: this level implies processes are monitored and measured with metrics, well beyond the ad hoc state described.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Defined and documented</b>: this level requires formal, documented processes, which the scenario explicitly states do not exist.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-044","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"An information security strategy should be reviewed and updated MOST appropriately:","options":["Only when a major breach occurs","Once, at the program's inception, and never again","On a periodic basis and when significant business or risk changes occur","Whenever a new employee joins the security team"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>On a periodic basis and when significant business or risk changes occur</strong> — regular scheduled reviews combined with event-driven updates ensure the strategy stays current with both routine planning cycles and unexpected material changes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Only when a major breach occurs</b>: waiting for a breach is reactive and misses the opportunity to proactively adjust to changing conditions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Once, at the program's inception, and never again</b>: a static strategy quickly becomes outdated as the business and threat landscape evolve.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whenever a new employee joins the security team</b>: staffing changes on the team are not a meaningful trigger for strategic review.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-045","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY purpose of establishing a security steering committee?","options":["To perform technical vulnerability scans","To replace the information security manager's role","To provide cross-functional oversight and support for security-related decisions and priorities","To conduct employee performance reviews"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To provide cross-functional oversight and support for security-related decisions and priorities</strong> — the steering committee brings together stakeholders from across the organization to guide priorities, resolve conflicts, and lend authority to security decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To perform technical vulnerability scans</b>: technical scanning is an operational security activity, not a governance committee function.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To replace the information security manager's role</b>: the committee supports and guides rather than replaces operational management roles.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To conduct employee performance reviews</b>: performance management is a human resources and line management responsibility, unrelated to the committee's purpose.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-046","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"med","q":"Segregation of duties in information security governance is PRIMARILY intended to:","options":["Reduce the number of employees needed","Increase the speed of system changes","Prevent any single individual from having unchecked control over a critical process","Eliminate the need for audit logging"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Prevent any single individual from having unchecked control over a critical process</strong> — segregation of duties reduces the risk of fraud, error, or abuse by ensuring no one person can both execute and conceal an inappropriate action.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the number of employees needed</b>: segregation of duties typically requires more, not fewer, people involved in a process.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the speed of system changes</b>: dividing responsibilities generally adds checks that can slow down processes, not speed them up.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for audit logging</b>: segregation of duties complements audit logging as a control; it does not replace the need for it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-047","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the purpose of a control framework such as COBIT in information security governance?","options":["To provide specific line-by-line code for software applications","To serve as a marketing document for the security team","To provide a structured set of governance and management objectives and practices","To replace the organization's legal department"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To provide a structured set of governance and management objectives and practices</strong> — COBIT offers a comprehensive framework of governance and management objectives that organizations can use to structure, evaluate, and improve their IT and security governance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To provide specific line-by-line code for software applications</b>: COBIT is a governance framework, not a software development or coding resource.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To serve as a marketing document for the security team</b>: it is a practical governance tool, not a promotional document.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To replace the organization's legal department</b>: COBIT supports governance practices but has no role in replacing legal functions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-048","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager wants to demonstrate return on security investment (ROSI) to justify a new control. Which approach BEST supports this?","options":["Comparing the cost of the control to the estimated reduction in expected loss from mitigated risk","Comparing the control's cost only to the vendor's list price","Estimating ROSI based solely on employee satisfaction surveys","Basing ROSI entirely on the number of features the control includes"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Comparing the cost of the control to the estimated reduction in expected loss from mitigated risk</strong> — a credible ROSI calculation weighs the investment against the quantified reduction in expected risk-related losses, tying cost directly to risk mitigation value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Comparing the control's cost only to the vendor's list price</b>: this only considers cost, not the value or risk reduction the control delivers.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Estimating ROSI based solely on employee satisfaction surveys</b>: satisfaction is subjective and unrelated to the actual financial risk reduction the control provides.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Basing ROSI entirely on the number of features the control includes</b>: feature count does not correlate with actual risk reduction or return on investment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-049","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would be the MOST appropriate first step in developing an information security strategy for a newly formed organization?","options":["Purchasing security tools based on industry trends","Hiring the maximum number of security analysts possible","Understanding the business model, objectives, and risk appetite","Publishing a security policy immediately"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Understanding the business model, objectives, and risk appetite</strong> — strategy formulation must begin with a clear understanding of what the business does, what it is trying to achieve, and how much risk it is willing to accept, before any controls or policies are defined.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Purchasing security tools based on industry trends</b>: buying tools before understanding business context risks misaligned or wasted investment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Hiring the maximum number of security analysts possible</b>: staffing decisions should follow from defined needs, not precede them.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publishing a security policy immediately</b>: policy should reflect strategic direction that has not yet been established for a brand-new organization.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-050","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the information security manager's MOST important consideration when a business unit wants to adopt a cloud service that will store regulated customer data?","options":["The vendor's stock market performance","The number of years the vendor has existed","The visual design of the vendor's user interface","Whether the vendor's contractual terms and controls satisfy applicable legal and regulatory obligations"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether the vendor's contractual terms and controls satisfy applicable legal and regulatory obligations</strong> — since regulated data is involved, the organization remains accountable for compliance, so contract terms and vendor controls must be verified against legal and regulatory requirements before adoption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The vendor's stock market performance</b>: financial market performance is not a meaningful indicator of data protection or compliance capability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The visual design of the vendor's user interface</b>: interface aesthetics have no bearing on regulatory compliance or data protection.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of years the vendor has existed</b>: longevity alone does not confirm that current controls meet applicable legal requirements.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-051","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes a security standard, as distinct from a policy?","options":["A high-level statement of management intent","A record of past security incidents","An optional guideline that may be disregarded","A mandatory, specific requirement that supports and enforces policy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A mandatory, specific requirement that supports and enforces policy</strong> — standards translate the high-level intent of policy into specific, mandatory requirements (e.g., minimum password length) that must be met.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A high-level statement of management intent</b>: this describes a policy, which sits above standards in the documentation hierarchy.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An optional guideline that may be disregarded</b>: standards are mandatory, unlike guidelines, which are advisory.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A record of past security incidents</b>: incident records are historical logs, unrelated to the definition of a standard.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-052","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"hard","q":"A newly hired information security manager finds that previous security initiatives failed due to lack of business engagement. What is the BEST FIRST action to rebuild trust and support?","options":["Immediately relaunch the same initiatives with more technical detail","Postpone all initiatives for at least two years","Bypass business units and report directly to external regulators","Conduct stakeholder interviews to understand business priorities and past concerns"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Conduct stakeholder interviews to understand business priorities and past concerns</strong> — understanding why prior initiatives failed and what matters to business stakeholders is essential before proposing new initiatives, and it demonstrates a collaborative approach that helps rebuild trust.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately relaunch the same initiatives with more technical detail</b>: repeating a failed approach without addressing the root cause of disengagement is unlikely to succeed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Bypass business units and report directly to external regulators</b>: this is an extreme and inappropriate escalation that damages internal relationships further.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Postpone all initiatives for at least two years</b>: an arbitrary, prolonged delay leaves the organization exposed to risk without addressing the underlying trust issue.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-053","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager is defining strategic objectives. Which characteristic makes an objective MOST useful for governance purposes?","options":["It is vague enough to apply to any situation","It avoids assigning any accountable owner","It is written exclusively in technical jargon","It is specific, measurable, and time-bound"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It is specific, measurable, and time-bound</strong> — well-formed objectives (following SMART-type criteria) allow progress to be tracked, accountability to be assigned, and success to be evaluated objectively.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It is vague enough to apply to any situation</b>: vague objectives cannot be measured or used to hold anyone accountable for outcomes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It is written exclusively in technical jargon</b>: jargon-heavy objectives are less accessible to business stakeholders who must support and fund them.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It avoids assigning any accountable owner</b>: without an owner, there is no accountability for achieving the objective.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-054","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would MOST likely indicate a weakness in an organization's information security governance structure?","options":["The security manager regularly briefs the audit committee","Security metrics are reviewed quarterly by the steering committee","Roles and responsibilities are documented in a RACI matrix","Security decisions are made independently by individual departments without any central oversight"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Security decisions are made independently by individual departments without any central oversight</strong> — decentralized decision-making without central coordination or oversight indicates a lack of unified governance, leading to inconsistent risk management across the enterprise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The security manager regularly briefs the audit committee</b>: regular briefings to an oversight body are a positive governance practice, not a weakness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Roles and responsibilities are documented in a RACI matrix</b>: documented accountability is a governance strength, not a weakness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Security metrics are reviewed quarterly by the steering committee</b>: periodic metric review by a governance body reflects good oversight practice.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-055","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization outsources its data processing to a third party. Which of the following BEST reflects the correct governance principle regarding accountability?","options":["Accountability for data protection transfers entirely to the third party","Only the third party's regulators are accountable","No one is accountable once data leaves the organization's network","The organization retains accountability for data protection even though processing is outsourced"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The organization retains accountability for data protection even though processing is outsourced</strong> — outsourcing can transfer operational responsibility for tasks, but the accountable organization remains ultimately answerable for ensuring the data is protected, including oversight of the third party.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accountability for data protection transfers entirely to the third party</b>: contracting out processing does not eliminate the originating organization's legal and governance accountability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No one is accountable once data leaves the organization's network</b>: accountability does not simply disappear based on data location; it remains with the data owner.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Only the third party's regulators are accountable</b>: regulators oversee compliance but are not themselves accountable parties for data protection.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-056","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants to benchmark its information security governance maturity against peers. Which approach is MOST appropriate?","options":["Compare only the total dollar amount spent on security","Assume maturity is proportional to company size","Rely solely on anecdotal comparisons from informal industry conversations","Use a recognized maturity model to assess capability levels across governance domains"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Use a recognized maturity model to assess capability levels across governance domains</strong> — a structured maturity model provides consistent, comparable criteria for assessing capability across governance domains, enabling meaningful benchmarking.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Compare only the total dollar amount spent on security</b>: spending level does not reliably indicate governance maturity or effectiveness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on anecdotal comparisons from informal industry conversations</b>: informal, unstructured comparisons lack the rigor needed for a valid benchmark.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assume maturity is proportional to company size</b>: organizational size does not necessarily correlate with governance maturity.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-057","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"easy","q":"Which communication approach is MOST likely to secure ongoing support from the board for the information security program?","options":["Technical jargon-heavy quarterly reports with no summary","Communication only through the annual external audit report","No communication unless a major incident occurs","Concise, risk-based updates highlighting trends, incidents, and business impact"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Concise, risk-based updates highlighting trends, incidents, and business impact</strong> — regular, digestible updates framed around business risk keep the board informed and engaged, supporting sustained commitment to the program.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Technical jargon-heavy quarterly reports with no summary</b>: overly technical reports without clear takeaways are difficult for a board to act on.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No communication unless a major incident occurs</b>: infrequent, reactive-only communication fails to build sustained board engagement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Communication only through the annual external audit report</b>: relying solely on an annual external report is too infrequent and indirect for ongoing governance oversight.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-058","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"med","q":"An information security steering committee is reviewing a proposal to accept a significant residual risk rather than fund a costly control. Whose approval is MOST appropriate for this risk acceptance decision?","options":["The systems administrator who identified the vulnerability","An external penetration tester","The help desk manager","A risk owner with the authority commensurate with the level of risk"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A risk owner with the authority commensurate with the level of risk</strong> — risk acceptance decisions should be made by someone with authority proportional to the potential impact, ensuring accountability aligns with decision-making power.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The systems administrator who identified the vulnerability</b>: this technical role identifies issues but typically lacks the authority to accept significant business risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The help desk manager</b>: this role has no authority over enterprise risk acceptance decisions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An external penetration tester</b>: testers identify vulnerabilities but have no organizational authority to accept risk on the company's behalf.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-059","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"hard","q":"A merger will combine two organizations with differing security cultures and risk appetites. What is the information security manager's BEST initial action regarding strategy?","options":["Immediately impose the acquiring organization's policies on the acquired entity","Ignore cultural differences since policy documents are similar","Maintain two entirely separate security programs indefinitely","Conduct a joint assessment of both organizations' risk profiles and governance practices to inform an integrated strategy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Conduct a joint assessment of both organizations' risk profiles and governance practices to inform an integrated strategy</strong> — understanding both organizations' current states, risks, and cultures is essential to designing an integrated strategy that manages combined risk effectively and gains buy-in from both sides.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately impose the acquiring organization's policies on the acquired entity</b>: imposing policies without assessment risks gaps, resistance, and overlooking risks unique to the acquired entity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Maintain two entirely separate security programs indefinitely</b>: indefinite separation prevents consistent enterprise-wide risk management and creates governance gaps.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore cultural differences since policy documents are similar</b>: similar documents do not guarantee similar practices or risk cultures, which must still be assessed.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-060","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the information security manager's MOST appropriate role regarding compliance with emerging privacy regulations?","options":["Sole owner of all compliance obligations across the enterprise","Final decision-maker on all litigation strategy","Uninvolved observer since privacy is solely a legal matter","Collaborative partner with legal and compliance functions to implement necessary controls"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Collaborative partner with legal and compliance functions to implement necessary controls</strong> — privacy compliance requires close collaboration between security, legal, and compliance to interpret requirements and implement the technical and procedural controls needed to meet them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sole owner of all compliance obligations across the enterprise</b>: compliance obligations span multiple functions and cannot be owned solely by security.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Uninvolved observer since privacy is solely a legal matter</b>: security plays an active role in implementing controls that satisfy privacy requirements, not a passive one.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Final decision-maker on all litigation strategy</b>: litigation strategy is a legal function outside the security manager's role.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-061","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST supports continuous improvement of an information security governance program?","options":["A one-time risk assessment performed at program launch","Relying exclusively on annual external audits for all feedback","Avoiding any changes to the original governance framework","Regular monitoring of metrics with feedback loops that inform strategy adjustments"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Regular monitoring of metrics with feedback loops that inform strategy adjustments</strong> — continuous improvement depends on ongoing measurement and using that data to refine strategy, controls, and priorities over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A one-time risk assessment performed at program launch</b>: a single point-in-time assessment quickly becomes outdated and cannot drive ongoing improvement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoiding any changes to the original governance framework</b>: refusing to adapt the framework prevents the program from responding to new risks or lessons learned.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Relying exclusively on annual external audits for all feedback</b>: annual audits alone provide infrequent feedback, insufficient for continuous, timely improvement.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-062","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following roles is typically responsible for implementing and maintaining technical safeguards on behalf of the data owner?","options":["Data custodian","Data owner","External regulator","Board of directors"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Data custodian</strong> — custodians are responsible for the day-to-day technical implementation and maintenance of controls that protect data, acting on behalf of and under direction from the data owner.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data owner</b>: the owner sets protection requirements and classification but typically delegates technical implementation to custodians.</span> <span class='qd'><b>External regulator</b>: regulators establish and enforce legal requirements; they do not implement internal technical safeguards.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Board of directors</b>: the board provides high-level governance oversight, not hands-on technical implementation.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-063","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is deciding between adopting a single comprehensive framework versus integrating elements from multiple frameworks (e.g., COBIT, ISO/IEC 27001, NIST CSF). Which factor should MOST influence this decision?","options":["Which framework has the shortest name","The number of pages in each framework's documentation","Which framework was adopted first by competitors","The organization's specific regulatory, operational, and business needs"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The organization's specific regulatory, operational, and business needs</strong> — the right combination of frameworks or single-framework approach should be driven by what actually addresses the organization's unique risk, regulatory, and operational context.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which framework has the shortest name</b>: naming characteristics are irrelevant to a framework's substantive fit or value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which framework was adopted first by competitors</b>: competitor adoption does not guarantee suitability for a different organization's unique context.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of pages in each framework's documentation</b>: document length has no bearing on whether a framework meets organizational needs.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-064","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST reflects a top-down approach to establishing information security governance?","options":["Individual system administrators independently define their own security controls","Business units create policies independently and report them to IT afterward","Security requirements emerge solely from end-user requests","The board and senior management establish direction, policy, and risk appetite that cascade through the organization"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The board and senior management establish direction, policy, and risk appetite that cascade through the organization</strong> — a top-down approach starts with governance direction from the highest levels of the organization, which is then translated into policy and operational practice throughout the enterprise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Individual system administrators independently define their own security controls</b>: this describes an uncoordinated, bottom-up approach lacking centralized direction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Security requirements emerge solely from end-user requests</b>: user-driven requirements reflect an ad hoc, reactive approach rather than governance-led direction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Business units create policies independently and report them to IT afterward</b>: this reflects decentralized policy-making without top-down alignment or oversight.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-065","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"med","q":"When drafting an information security policy, which of the following is MOST important to ensure it remains enforceable?","options":["Using highly technical language understood only by engineers","Avoiding any reference to consequences for non-compliance","Making the policy as long and detailed as possible","Aligning the policy with actual organizational capability and obtaining management approval"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Aligning the policy with actual organizational capability and obtaining management approval</strong> — a policy is enforceable only when it reflects what the organization can realistically implement and has the formal backing of management authority.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using highly technical language understood only by engineers</b>: overly technical wording reduces comprehension and buy-in across the broader workforce that must comply.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Making the policy as long and detailed as possible</b>: excessive length and detail can reduce clarity and practical usability rather than improve enforceability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoiding any reference to consequences for non-compliance</b>: omitting consequences weakens the policy's enforceability and signals that violations carry no real accountability.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-066","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager is preparing a presentation for the audit committee. Which of the following would be MOST relevant to include?","options":["A detailed list of every configuration setting on all servers","A copy of every vendor contract in full","The personal performance reviews of the security team","A summary of key risks, trends, and the status of remediation efforts"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A summary of key risks, trends, and the status of remediation efforts</strong> — an audit committee needs a concise, risk-focused summary to fulfill its oversight responsibilities, not granular technical or administrative detail.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A detailed list of every configuration setting on all servers</b>: this level of technical granularity is inappropriate and unhelpful for governance-level oversight.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The personal performance reviews of the security team</b>: individual HR matters are unrelated to the committee's oversight of security risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A copy of every vendor contract in full</b>: full contracts are excessive detail; relevant risk implications should be summarized instead.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-067","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes \"risk appetite\" in the context of information security governance?","options":["The exact dollar amount budgeted for security tools","The maximum number of employees allowed in the security department","The number of open vulnerabilities at any given time","The amount and type of risk an organization is willing to accept in pursuit of its objectives"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The amount and type of risk an organization is willing to accept in pursuit of its objectives</strong> — risk appetite is a governance concept defining the level of risk exposure the organization considers acceptable while pursuing its strategic objectives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The exact dollar amount budgeted for security tools</b>: budget figures are a resourcing decision, not a definition of acceptable risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of open vulnerabilities at any given time</b>: vulnerability counts are an operational metric, not a statement of strategic risk tolerance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The maximum number of employees allowed in the security department</b>: staffing limits are unrelated to the concept of risk appetite.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-068","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager is tasked with improving governance maturity from \"defined\" to \"managed and measurable.\" Which action BEST supports this transition?","options":["Writing the first set of formal policies for the organization","Delegating all governance responsibility to a single junior analyst","Eliminating all existing documented procedures","Implementing quantitative metrics and monitoring processes to measure control performance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Implementing quantitative metrics and monitoring processes to measure control performance</strong> — moving from \"defined\" (documented processes) to \"managed and measurable\" requires adding quantitative measurement and monitoring capability to assess how well those processes perform.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Writing the first set of formal policies for the organization</b>: creating initial formal policies corresponds to reaching the \"defined\" level, which the organization has already achieved.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminating all existing documented procedures</b>: removing documentation would regress maturity rather than advance it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delegating all governance responsibility to a single junior analyst</b>: concentrating governance in one junior role does not build the measurement capability needed for this maturity transition.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-069","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY benefit of clearly defined and communicated information security roles and responsibilities?","options":["It guarantees zero security incidents","It allows the organization to reduce its insurance coverage","It eliminates the need for a security policy","It reduces ambiguity and supports accountability when risk decisions are made"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>It reduces ambiguity and supports accountability when risk decisions are made</strong> — clear roles ensure everyone understands what is expected of them, which supports consistent execution and clear accountability when issues or decisions arise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It guarantees zero security incidents</b>: no amount of role clarity can guarantee the complete absence of incidents.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for a security policy</b>: roles and policy are complementary governance elements; one does not replace the other.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It allows the organization to reduce its insurance coverage</b>: role clarity has no direct bearing on insurance coverage decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-070","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager learns that a new industry regulation will require breach notification within 72 hours. What is the MOST appropriate immediate action?","options":["Ignore the requirement until a breach actually occurs","Wait for a competitor to be fined before taking action","Terminate the incident response plan entirely","Assess current incident response capability against the new requirement and address any gaps"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Assess current incident response capability against the new requirement and address any gaps</strong> — proactively evaluating whether existing processes can meet the new notification timeline allows the organization to close gaps before a real incident tests its compliance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the requirement until a breach actually occurs</b>: waiting until a breach happens to discover non-compliance creates significant legal and reputational exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Terminate the incident response plan entirely</b>: eliminating the plan removes an essential capability rather than improving it to meet the new requirement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Wait for a competitor to be fined before taking action</b>: relying on a competitor's misfortune as a trigger is reactive and leaves the organization needlessly exposed.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-071","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"hard","q":"Two executives disagree on the acceptable level of risk for a new digital product launch. The information security manager's BEST role in this situation is to:","options":["Make the final risk acceptance decision personally","Publicly side with whichever executive has more seniority","Refuse to participate in the discussion","Facilitate a risk-informed discussion and ensure the decision is escalated to someone with appropriate authority"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Facilitate a risk-informed discussion and ensure the decision is escalated to someone with appropriate authority</strong> — the security manager's role is to provide risk expertise and ensure the decision is made by someone with the proper authority, not to unilaterally decide or avoid the issue.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Make the final risk acceptance decision personally</b>: significant risk acceptance decisions typically exceed the security manager's authority and belong with accountable business leadership.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Refuse to participate in the discussion</b>: disengaging fails to provide the risk expertise needed to inform a sound decision.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publicly side with whichever executive has more seniority</b>: basing a risk decision on seniority rather than risk analysis undermines objective governance.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-072","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is an example of a governance-level activity rather than a management-level activity?","options":["Configuring a firewall rule set","Running a vulnerability scan","Patching a vulnerable server","Approving the enterprise information security strategy"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Approving the enterprise information security strategy</strong> — approving strategic direction is an oversight and direction-setting function that belongs to governance, distinct from the operational execution tasks handled by management.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Configuring a firewall rule set</b>: this is a hands-on technical task performed as part of operational management.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Patching a vulnerable server</b>: patching is a routine operational activity carried out by technical staff.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Running a vulnerability scan</b>: scanning is a technical assessment activity within the management/operational layer.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-073","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would MOST likely improve the effectiveness of an information security steering committee?","options":["Meeting only once every three years","Excluding minutes or records of decisions made","Allowing meetings to occur without any agenda","Establishing a documented charter with clear objectives, authority, and meeting cadence"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Establishing a documented charter with clear objectives, authority, and meeting cadence</strong> — a formal charter provides the committee with clear purpose, defined authority, and operational structure, which improves consistency and effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Meeting only once every three years</b>: infrequent meetings prevent the committee from providing timely oversight and responsiveness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing meetings to occur without any agenda</b>: unstructured meetings without an agenda tend to be unproductive and fail to address priority issues.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Excluding minutes or records of decisions made</b>: lack of documentation undermines accountability and traceability of governance decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-074","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"An organization's business strategy shifts toward rapid digital expansion into new markets. The information security manager's MOST appropriate response is to:","options":["Maintain the existing security strategy unchanged","Delegate the entire security strategy to the new market's local staff","Recommend halting the business expansion","Reassess the security strategy to address new risks introduced by the expansion"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Reassess the security strategy to address new risks introduced by the expansion</strong> — a significant shift in business direction introduces new risks and requirements that the security strategy must be updated to address, keeping it aligned with the business.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Maintain the existing security strategy unchanged</b>: an unchanged strategy risks failing to address new risks introduced by market expansion.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Recommend halting the business expansion</b>: security should enable business objectives through appropriate risk management, not obstruct legitimate business strategy.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delegate the entire security strategy to the new market's local staff</b>: decentralizing strategic ownership entirely risks losing enterprise-wide consistency and oversight.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-075","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager discovers that a business unit has been making its own risk acceptance decisions without following the enterprise risk governance process. What is the BEST way to address this?","options":["Publicly reprimand the business unit leader in a company-wide email","Terminate the business unit's access to all systems immediately","Allow the practice to continue since the business unit understands its own risk","Reinforce the governance process, clarify authority levels, and ensure retroactive review of the decisions made"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Reinforce the governance process, clarify authority levels, and ensure retroactive review of the decisions made</strong> — restoring proper governance requires clarifying who holds risk acceptance authority, reinforcing the process going forward, and reviewing the unauthorized decisions to ensure risk is understood and managed appropriately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publicly reprimand the business unit leader in a company-wide email</b>: a public reprimand is unprofessional and does not fix the underlying process gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allow the practice to continue since the business unit understands its own risk</b>: bypassing governance undermines enterprise-wide risk oversight and consistency, regardless of local understanding.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Terminate the business unit's access to all systems immediately</b>: this is a disproportionate operational disruption that does not address the governance gap directly.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-076","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the concept of \"three lines of defense\" as applied to information security governance?","options":["Three separate firewalls placed in sequence","A model distinguishing operational management, risk/compliance oversight, and independent audit assurance","Three different antivirus vendors used simultaneously","Three copies of every backup stored offsite"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A model distinguishing operational management, risk/compliance oversight, and independent audit assurance</strong> — the three lines of defense model separates day-to-day risk-owning operations, oversight/compliance functions, and independent audit assurance to strengthen overall governance and control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Three separate firewalls placed in sequence</b>: this describes a technical network architecture concept, not the governance model referenced.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Three different antivirus vendors used simultaneously</b>: vendor diversity for endpoint protection is unrelated to the governance concept described.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Three copies of every backup stored offsite</b>: this describes backup redundancy practice, not a governance oversight model.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-077","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager wants to track whether security awareness training is having a real effect on behavior. Which metric is MOST useful for this purpose?","options":["Number of employees who received a training invitation email","Percentage reduction in successful phishing simulation click rates over time","Total minutes of training video produced","Number of different training vendors used"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Percentage reduction in successful phishing simulation click rates over time</strong> — a declining click rate on simulated phishing attempts is a behavioral outcome metric that directly reflects whether training is changing employee behavior.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of employees who received a training invitation email</b>: this measures distribution, not whether training changed behavior.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Total minutes of training video produced</b>: content volume is an input measure with no connection to behavioral outcomes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of different training vendors used</b>: vendor count is irrelevant to measuring the actual effectiveness of training.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-078","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager must choose between a strategy emphasizing rapid deployment of new controls versus one emphasizing careful, phased implementation with change management. In a highly regulated, risk-averse organization, which approach is generally MOST appropriate?","options":["Rapid deployment regardless of organizational readiness","A phased approach with change management aligned to organizational capacity and culture","No implementation until a perfect, risk-free solution is found","Delegating the choice entirely to the software vendor"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A phased approach with change management aligned to organizational capacity and culture</strong> — in a risk-averse, regulated environment, a careful, phased rollout with proper change management reduces disruption and resistance while still making steady progress toward the strategy's goals.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rapid deployment regardless of organizational readiness</b>: rushing implementation without considering organizational readiness increases the risk of failure and disruption, especially in a risk-averse culture.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No implementation until a perfect, risk-free solution is found</b>: waiting for a nonexistent risk-free solution leaves current risks unaddressed indefinitely.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delegating the choice entirely to the software vendor</b>: implementation approach decisions should be driven by organizational context, not outsourced to a vendor's preference.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-079","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the information security manager's role when a regulator issues new guidance affecting information handling practices?","options":["Disregard the guidance since it is not legally binding","Evaluate the guidance and recommend appropriate policy or control updates to relevant stakeholders","Immediately dismiss all affected employees","Publicly comment on the regulator's authority to issue guidance"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Evaluate the guidance and recommend appropriate policy or control updates to relevant stakeholders</strong> — the security manager should analyze the practical impact of new guidance and work with stakeholders to update policies and controls as appropriate, even if the guidance is not strictly binding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disregard the guidance since it is not legally binding</b>: regulatory guidance often signals expectations that can affect examinations or enforcement, so it should not be ignored outright.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately dismiss all affected employees</b>: this is an extreme, unrelated overreaction with no connection to responding to regulatory guidance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Publicly comment on the regulator's authority to issue guidance</b>: challenging regulatory authority publicly is outside the security manager's role and inappropriate.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-080","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"med","q":"An information security policy states a requirement that conflicts with an operational business need. What is the BEST approach for the information security manager?","options":["Ignore the conflict and let the business unit violate the policy quietly","Review the conflict, evaluate risk trade-offs, and pursue a formal exception or policy revision process","Rewrite the policy alone without consulting anyone","Immediately shut down the conflicting business operation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Review the conflict, evaluate risk trade-offs, and pursue a formal exception or policy revision process</strong> — conflicts between policy and business need should be resolved transparently through a formal process that weighs risk and either grants a documented exception or updates the policy appropriately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the conflict and let the business unit violate the policy quietly</b>: tacitly allowing silent noncompliance undermines governance and leaves risk unmanaged and undocumented.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rewrite the policy alone without consulting anyone</b>: unilateral rewriting bypasses the collaborative review needed to ensure the change is sound and properly approved.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately shut down the conflicting business operation</b>: this disproportionate response does not consider whether a reasonable exception or accommodation could resolve the conflict.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-081","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following is the BEST way for an information security manager to build credibility with the executive team early in their tenure?","options":["Immediately proposing a complete overhaul of all existing controls","Delivering a few well-scoped, visible improvements that address known business risks","Avoiding any public presentations until year two","Criticizing the previous security manager's decisions in meetings"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Delivering a few well-scoped, visible improvements that address known business risks</strong> — early, tangible wins that address recognized business risks demonstrate competence and build trust, laying the foundation for larger initiatives later.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately proposing a complete overhaul of all existing controls</b>: a sweeping overhaul without established credibility risks resistance and may be poorly received.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoiding any public presentations until year two</b>: delaying visible engagement for a year misses valuable opportunities to build relationships and credibility early.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Criticizing the previous security manager's decisions in meetings</b>: publicly criticizing a predecessor is unprofessional and damages trust rather than building it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-082","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"easy","q":"An information security strategy that is well-aligned with business objectives will MOST likely result in:","options":["Elimination of the security budget over time","Security initiatives that are prioritized and funded based on business value and risk","A reduction in the number of employees across the company","Complete independence of the security function from business operations"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Security initiatives that are prioritized and funded based on business value and risk</strong> — alignment ensures security investments are prioritized according to what matters most to the business, improving both funding decisions and risk outcomes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Elimination of the security budget over time</b>: good alignment justifies appropriate funding, not the elimination of investment in security.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A reduction in the number of employees across the company</b>: strategic alignment has no inherent connection to overall company staffing levels.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Complete independence of the security function from business operations</b>: alignment actually requires closer integration with business operations, not independence from them.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-083","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following would BEST help an information security manager assess the current state of governance maturity before setting improvement targets?","options":["A vendor sales pitch for new security software","A structured maturity assessment using a recognized capability model","An informal poll of the security team's opinions","A review of competitor press releases"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A structured maturity assessment using a recognized capability model</strong> — a formal maturity assessment provides an objective, structured baseline across governance domains, which is necessary before setting meaningful improvement targets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A vendor sales pitch for new security software</b>: vendor pitches are commercially biased and not a reliable basis for assessing governance maturity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An informal poll of the security team's opinions</b>: informal, subjective opinions lack the rigor and objectivity of a structured assessment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A review of competitor press releases</b>: public press releases rarely reveal accurate, detailed internal governance maturity information.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-084","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager notices overlapping responsibilities between the risk management function and the security function, causing confusion. What is the BEST way to resolve this?","options":["Ignore the overlap since both functions are trying to reduce risk","Clarify and document distinct roles, responsibilities, and escalation paths between the two functions","Merge both functions without any planning or transition","Direct all risk decisions to the security function exclusively going forward"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Clarify and document distinct roles, responsibilities, and escalation paths between the two functions</strong> — resolving overlapping accountability requires clearly defining who does what and how issues are escalated, restoring clarity and efficiency between the functions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the overlap since both functions are trying to reduce risk</b>: shared goals do not eliminate the confusion and inefficiency caused by unclear roles.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Merge both functions without any planning or transition</b>: an unplanned merger risks losing needed expertise and creating further disruption.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Direct all risk decisions to the security function exclusively going forward</b>: this ignores the distinct value and expertise the risk management function provides.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-085","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization has implemented COBIT governance objectives but continues to experience security incidents due to poor execution at the operational level. This scenario BEST illustrates that:","options":["COBIT is an ineffective framework and should be abandoned","Governance frameworks alone do not guarantee effective management-level execution","Security incidents are always caused by governance failures","COBIT replaces the need for management processes"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Governance frameworks alone do not guarantee effective management-level execution</strong> — a governance framework sets direction and objectives, but actual risk reduction depends on how well management executes and operationalizes those objectives; a gap in execution is a management issue, not necessarily a governance framework flaw.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>COBIT is an ineffective framework and should be abandoned</b>: the framework itself is not necessarily flawed; the issue described is execution, which is a separate layer.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Security incidents are always caused by governance failures</b>: this is an overgeneralization; many incidents stem from operational or management execution issues, not governance design.</span> <span class='qd'><b>COBIT replaces the need for management processes</b>: COBIT explicitly distinguishes and requires both governance and management processes; it does not replace the need for the latter.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-086","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST helps ensure that information security is considered early in new business initiatives rather than as an afterthought?","options":["Requiring security sign-off only after full production deployment","Embedding a security representative in project and change management processes from initiation","Conducting an annual, standalone security review disconnected from projects","Allowing each project manager to decide independently whether security should be involved"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Embedding a security representative in project and change management processes from initiation</strong> — involving security from the earliest stages of project and change management ensures risks are identified and addressed proactively rather than retrofitted later at greater cost and risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requiring security sign-off only after full production deployment</b>: reviewing security only after deployment is far too late to influence design decisions cost-effectively.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Conducting an annual, standalone security review disconnected from projects</b>: an annual review disconnected from actual project timelines fails to provide timely input during development.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing each project manager to decide independently whether security should be involved</b>: leaving involvement optional and inconsistent risks many projects bypassing security review entirely.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-087","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is generally considered a LAGGING indicator in information security metrics?","options":["Number of employees who completed security training this month","Number of security incidents that occurred last quarter","Number of vulnerability scans scheduled for next month","Percentage of systems covered by planned patch deployment"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Number of security incidents that occurred last quarter</strong> — this measures outcomes that have already happened, making it a lagging indicator that reflects past performance rather than predicting future risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of employees who completed security training this month</b>: this is more of a leading indicator, reflecting a proactive activity intended to reduce future risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of vulnerability scans scheduled for next month</b>: this is a forward-looking planning measure, not a lagging outcome.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Percentage of systems covered by planned patch deployment</b>: this reflects planned proactive coverage, functioning as a leading rather than lagging indicator.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-088","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"When presenting the information security strategy to the board, the information security manager should focus PRIMARILY on:","options":["A line-by-line review of every technical control implemented","How the strategy manages risk to support achievement of business objectives","The personal career goals of the security team","A detailed history of the security department's founding"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>How the strategy manages risk to support achievement of business objectives</strong> — the board's interest is in how security risk is managed in service of the organization's objectives, which should be the central theme of any strategy presentation to them.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A line-by-line review of every technical control implemented</b>: this level of technical detail is inappropriate and unhelpful for a board-level audience.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The personal career goals of the security team</b>: staff career aspirations are irrelevant to the board's governance interest in strategy.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A detailed history of the security department's founding</b>: historical background does not inform the board's forward-looking risk and strategy decisions.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-089","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is expanding into a country with strict data localization laws requiring certain data to remain within its borders. The information security manager's BEST first step is to:","options":["Proceed with the existing global architecture unchanged","Assess the impact of the localization requirement on current data flows and architecture, then plan necessary adjustments","Refuse to support the business expansion","Store all company data in that country regardless of classification or necessity"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Assess the impact of the localization requirement on current data flows and architecture, then plan necessary adjustments</strong> — understanding how the new legal requirement affects existing data flows and systems is essential before designing compliant adjustments to architecture or processes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Proceed with the existing global architecture unchanged</b>: ignoring the new legal requirement risks noncompliance and potential penalties.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Refuse to support the business expansion</b>: security should work to enable compliant expansion rather than obstruct legitimate business strategy outright.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Store all company data in that country regardless of classification or necessity</b>: an indiscriminate approach ignores the principle of addressing only the data actually subject to the localization requirement.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-090","domain":1,"obj":"1B2","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the value of including legal counsel as a member of the information security steering committee?","options":["Legal counsel can perform technical vulnerability assessments","Legal counsel provides insight on regulatory obligations and contractual/liability risk relevant to security decisions","Legal counsel replaces the need for a data protection officer","Legal counsel is responsible for patch management"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Legal counsel provides insight on regulatory obligations and contractual/liability risk relevant to security decisions</strong> — legal expertise ensures that governance decisions properly account for regulatory, contractual, and liability considerations that affect the organization's risk posture.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Legal counsel can perform technical vulnerability assessments</b>: technical assessments require specialized security skills that are outside a legal role's function.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Legal counsel replaces the need for a data protection officer</b>: a dedicated privacy role serves a distinct function and is not replaced by having legal representation on the committee.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Legal counsel is responsible for patch management</b>: patch management is an operational technical activity unrelated to the legal function.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-091","domain":1,"obj":"1A3","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the primary responsibility of an information asset owner regarding data classification?","options":["Writing the antivirus signature updates","Determining the appropriate classification level and protection requirements for the asset","Configuring network switches","Performing daily system backups"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Determining the appropriate classification level and protection requirements for the asset</strong> — the asset owner is accountable for deciding how sensitive the data is and what level of protection it requires, guiding the controls that custodians will implement.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Writing the antivirus signature updates</b>: this is a vendor or technical operations task unrelated to the owner's classification responsibility.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Configuring network switches</b>: network configuration is a technical custodial task, not an ownership responsibility.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Performing daily system backups</b>: backup execution is an operational custodial task delegated by, not performed by, the owner.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-092","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"An information security manager is asked to define success criteria for the security strategy's first year. The MOST appropriate criteria would:","options":["Focus solely on the number of new tools purchased","Include measurable outcomes tied to risk reduction and business enablement","Focus only on staff satisfaction scores","Avoid setting any criteria to allow maximum flexibility"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Include measurable outcomes tied to risk reduction and business enablement</strong> — success criteria should be tangible and tied to the strategy's actual purpose: reducing risk and enabling the business, so progress can be objectively evaluated.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Focus solely on the number of new tools purchased</b>: tool acquisition is an input, not an outcome, and does not demonstrate actual risk reduction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Focus only on staff satisfaction scores</b>: staff sentiment alone does not capture whether the strategy is achieving its risk and business goals.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoid setting any criteria to allow maximum flexibility</b>: without defined criteria, there is no way to evaluate whether the strategy succeeded.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-093","domain":1,"obj":"1B1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's board wants independent assurance that the information security governance program is operating effectively. Which of the following provides the MOST objective assurance?","options":["A self-assessment performed by the information security manager","An independent audit or assessment performed by internal audit or a qualified external party","A survey of employee opinions about security","A summary provided by the marketing department"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An independent audit or assessment performed by internal audit or a qualified external party</strong> — independent assurance requires evaluation by a party free from operational bias, such as internal audit or an external assessor, to objectively validate governance effectiveness.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A self-assessment performed by the information security manager</b>: a self-assessment lacks independence since the same person responsible for the program is evaluating it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A survey of employee opinions about security</b>: employee perception surveys are subjective and do not constitute an objective assurance mechanism.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A summary provided by the marketing department</b>: marketing has no relevant expertise or independence to assess governance effectiveness.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-094","domain":1,"obj":"1A4","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST explains why an organization might choose to map its controls to multiple frameworks (e.g., ISO/IEC 27001 and a regional regulatory standard) rather than a single framework?","options":["To make the compliance program more confusing intentionally","To efficiently demonstrate compliance with multiple sets of obligations using a common control set","Because using multiple frameworks is required by law in every country","To avoid the need for a risk assessment altogether"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To efficiently demonstrate compliance with multiple sets of obligations using a common control set</strong> — mapping controls across frameworks allows an organization to satisfy overlapping regulatory and standards-based obligations efficiently without duplicating effort for each one separately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To make the compliance program more confusing intentionally</b>: adding confusion is never a legitimate governance objective.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Because using multiple frameworks is required by law in every country</b>: there is no universal legal mandate requiring multi-framework mapping in every jurisdiction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To avoid the need for a risk assessment altogether</b>: framework mapping does not eliminate the ongoing need for risk assessment.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-095","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager has limited budget and must choose between funding a governance improvement initiative (e.g., formal risk committee) or a technical control (e.g., additional endpoint detection capability). Which consideration should be MOST influential in this decision?","options":["Which option has a flashier vendor demo","Which option addresses the greatest identified business risk relative to its cost","Which option is easier to implement regardless of risk impact","Which option was requested most recently"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Which option addresses the greatest identified business risk relative to its cost</strong> — with limited resources, prioritization should be driven by a risk-based cost-benefit comparison to ensure the investment delivers the greatest risk reduction for the organization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which option has a flashier vendor demo</b>: an impressive demonstration has no bearing on actual risk reduction value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which option is easier to implement regardless of risk impact</b>: prioritizing ease of implementation over risk impact can lead to poor allocation of limited resources.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which option was requested most recently</b>: recency of a request is not a valid basis for risk-based prioritization.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-096","domain":1,"obj":"1A5","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST illustrates the concept of \"due diligence\" in an information security governance context?","options":["Purchasing the most expensive security product available","Taking reasonable, documented steps to identify and manage risk before a decision or event occurs","Waiting until after an incident to investigate what happened","Assuming all third parties are automatically compliant with regulations"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Taking reasonable, documented steps to identify and manage risk before a decision or event occurs</strong> — due diligence refers to the proactive, documented care an organization exercises to understand and manage risk before committing to a decision, such as a vendor relationship or business initiative.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Purchasing the most expensive security product available</b>: cost of a purchase does not equate to exercising diligence in risk identification and management.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Waiting until after an incident to investigate what happened</b>: this describes a reactive investigation, which is the opposite of proactive due diligence.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assuming all third parties are automatically compliant with regulations</b>: making unverified assumptions about third-party compliance is a failure of due diligence, not an example of it.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-097","domain":1,"obj":"1B3","diff":"easy","q":"An information security policy exception process is BEST described as a mechanism to:","options":["Permanently eliminate specific policy requirements","Formally document, assess, and approve or deny deviations from policy with appropriate risk oversight","Allow any employee to bypass policy without review","Replace the need for a documented security policy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Formally document, assess, and approve or deny deviations from policy with appropriate risk oversight</strong> — an exception process provides a controlled, transparent way to evaluate and approve necessary deviations from policy while maintaining appropriate risk visibility and accountability.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Permanently eliminate specific policy requirements</b>: exceptions are typically temporary and case-specific, not permanent removals of a requirement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allow any employee to bypass policy without review</b>: an exception process specifically requires formal review and approval, not unreviewed bypassing.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for a documented security policy</b>: the exception process operates within the framework of an existing policy; it does not replace the policy itself.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-098","domain":1,"obj":"1A1","diff":"med","q":"Which of the following BEST reflects a mature approach to integrating information security strategy with enterprise risk management (ERM)?","options":["Treating information security risk as entirely separate from other enterprise risks","Incorporating information security risk into the organization's overall enterprise risk register and reporting","Reporting security risk only to the IT department","Excluding security risk from any board-level risk discussions"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Incorporating information security risk into the organization's overall enterprise risk register and reporting</strong> — mature integration means security risk is treated as a component of overall enterprise risk, tracked and reported alongside financial, operational, and other risk categories for holistic oversight.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Treating information security risk as entirely separate from other enterprise risks</b>: siloing security risk from other enterprise risks prevents a holistic view of organizational exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reporting security risk only to the IT department</b>: limiting visibility to IT excludes the broader governance oversight that ERM integration requires.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Excluding security risk from any board-level risk discussions</b>: omitting security risk from board discussions contradicts the goal of enterprise-wide risk visibility.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-099","domain":1,"obj":"1B4","diff":"hard","q":"An information security manager wants to avoid \"vanity metrics\" in governance reporting. Which of the following BEST exemplifies a vanity metric to avoid?","options":["Mean time to detect and contain incidents","Total number of security awareness emails sent, without measuring behavior change","Percentage of critical assets covered by a risk assessment","Trend in the number of high-risk findings remediated within SLA"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Total number of security awareness emails sent, without measuring behavior change</strong> — this metric counts an activity volume without connecting it to any meaningful outcome, making it a vanity metric that looks impressive but does not indicate actual risk reduction or behavior change.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Mean time to detect and contain incidents</b>: this is an outcome-oriented operational metric that meaningfully reflects response capability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Percentage of critical assets covered by a risk assessment</b>: this measures meaningful risk visibility coverage, not a superficial activity count.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Trend in the number of high-risk findings remediated within SLA</b>: this tracks a substantive outcome connected directly to risk reduction over time.</span>"},
{"id":"D1-100","domain":1,"obj":"1A2","diff":"med","q":"Ultimately, the effectiveness of information security governance is BEST measured by the degree to which it:","options":["Produces the largest possible number of policy documents","Enables the organization to achieve its objectives while keeping risk within an acceptable, well-understood level","Minimizes all interaction between security and business units","Relies exclusively on the personal expertise of one individual"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Enables the organization to achieve its objectives while keeping risk within an acceptable, well-understood level</strong> — the ultimate test of governance effectiveness is whether it supports the organization in achieving its goals while ensuring risk remains within a consciously accepted, well-understood boundary.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Produces the largest possible number of policy documents</b>: sheer document volume is an output measure with no inherent link to actual effectiveness.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Minimizes all interaction between security and business units</b>: effective governance actually requires close collaboration with business units, not minimized interaction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Relies exclusively on the personal expertise of one individual</b>: sustainable, mature governance is institutionalized in processes and structures, not dependent on a single person.</span>"}
]);
